'''''Star Wars: The Interactive Video Board Game''''' (subtitled ''Assault on the Death Star'') is a [[1996]] board game released by [[Hasbro]].

==Opening crawl==
{{OpeningCrawl
|name=ASSAULT ON THE DEATH STAR
|text=The Galactic Empire's second
Death Star is almost complete. The
Emperor, concerned that the Rebels
have discovered the location of his
new weapon, has ordered it to be
moved near the moon of Endor,
where it can be completed in
secret.

On board his Star Destroyer, Lord
Vader receives word of a large
Rebel supply base on D'rinba IV
and orders the Death Star, en route
for Endor, to divert there.

The Rebel Alliance intercepts this
transmission and assembles a
small team of Force-sensitive
Rebels. Using a stolen Imperial
Freighter, and cloaked by the
Force, they board the Death Star.
They must disable it before it is
within superlaser range of D'rinba IV.

But, at the start of their mission,
as the Rebels are concealed in the
Shuttle Bays, the Death Star has
another arrival....
}}

==Plot summary {{SectionFlag|1}}==
Following a failed attempt by the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] to destroy the [[Death Star II/Legends|second Death Star]], [[Emperor/Legends|Emperor]] [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]] orders [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] to take command of the battlestation and move it to [[Endor/Legends|the forest moon of Endor]] to be completed in secret. Shortly thereafter, he learns of a major [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] supply base on the planet [[D'rinba IV]] and diverts its course to the planet, intending to use the battlestation's [[Superlaser/Legends|superlaser]] to destroy it. Intercepting this information, the Alliance assembles a team of [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] individuals to sneak on board and disable the station. However, Vader soon learns of their presence and has the station put on alert. The situation becomes a race against time for the members of the infiltration party, as they must attempt to succeed in their mission while avoiding the station's [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtrooper]] contingent and, late in the mission, a party member's fall to the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|Dark side of the Force]].<ref name="SW VCR manual">{{Hasbro|subdomain=www|url=common/instruct/Star_Wars_Assault_on_the_Death_Star_VCR_Board_Game.pdf|text=Star Wars Assault on the Death Star VCR Board Game instructions}}</ref>

==Contents==
[[File:InteractiveGameBoard.png|thumb|right|The game board]]
The game is based on cards and die, and requires the assembly of various three-dimensional components.<ref name="SW VCR manual" />
*1 60-Minute VHS videotape
*1 Game Board
*13 ''Star Wars'' Figures
*36 Cardboard Explosives
*6 Force Level Indicators
*2 Combat Disks
*1 Death Star Reactor Core
*80 Cards
*Die and Instructions

==Development==
===Production===
{{Quote|The photography had to match the original film, but we didn't have the facilities or the money to do it. So I had to get the same results in a different sort of way, with different equipment.|Gilbert Taylor|<ref name="insider95">{{InsiderCite|95|Taylor Made: Special Edition}}</ref>}}
[[File:Vader_video.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The shooting of a Vader scene with Director Phil Attfield and DOP Gil Taylor]]
The game contains a VHS tape that is played on a television screen as the players play the game. In the tape, Vader arrives on board the [[Death Star II/Legends|second Death Star]] to take command of the station to destroy a [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] supply base on the planet [[D'rinba IV]]. The player characters are tasked with the mission to stop him.

The tape contains scenes from the [[original trilogy]] mixed with footage shot specifically for the tape by [[Gilbert Taylor]], cinematographer for [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']]. The footage, shot over the course of two days, features [[David Prowse]] and [[James Earl Jones]] reprising their roles as the physical presence and voice of [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] respectively. Prowse wore an original Vader costume from the [[Lucasfilm Archives]]. Production Design was by Frank Walsh (www.fwalsh.com), who went on to design sets for the Netflix sci-fi series ''Lost in Space''. Sets were built by Dick George Productions, who previously worked on some of the sets for ''A New Hope''.<ref name="insider95" />

==Continuity==
This game was referenced in ''[[The Dark Forces Saga]]'', a series of online adventure scenarios for the [[Wizards of the Coast]] ''Star Wars'' RPG line published on their website. Written by [[Abel G. Peña]], this series canonizes four of the VCR game's player characters as [[Kyle Katarn]] (from ''[[Star Wars: Dark Forces]]''), [[Lumiya|Shira Brie]] (from the [[Marvel Comics]] [[Star Wars (1977)|''Star Wars'']] series), [[Corwin Shelvay/Legends|Corwin Shelvay]] (from [[West End Games]]'s ''Star Wars'' RPG material), and [[Erling Tredway]] (also from West End Games's ''Star Wars'' RPG material.)<ref name="DFS">{{Wizards|url=default.asp?x=starwars/article/sw20050407a|serieslink=The Dark Forces Saga|text=Part 1}}</ref>

